[{"id":44279,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["Diffraction","Scattering","Reflection","Refraction"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Rayleigh scattering applies to particles that are small with respect to wavelengths of light.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44228,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["Both $(\\mathbf{A})$ and $(\\mathbf{R})$ are true but $(\\mathbf{R})$ is not the correct explanation of $(\\mathbf{A})$","Both $(\\mathbf{A})$ and $(\\mathbf{R})$ are true and $(\\mathbf{R})$ is the correct explanation of $(\\mathbf{A})$","(A) is true but (R) is false","$(A)$ is false but (R) is true"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\beta(\\text { fringe width })=\\frac{\\lambda D}{d}$\n\nIn denser medium, $\\lambda \\downarrow \\Rightarrow \\beta \\downarrow$ $\\Rightarrow$ fringe come closer\n\nAlso, $\\mu=\\frac{\\mathrm{c}}{\\mathrm{V}} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{V}=\\frac{\\mathrm{c}}{\\mu}$\nFrequency remains same,\n$\\Rightarrow \\mu=\\frac{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{vac} .} \\mathrm{f}}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{med}} \\mathrm{f}} \\Rightarrow \\lambda_{\\mathrm{med}}=\\frac{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{vac} .}}{\\mu}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44304,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.0</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b077eab1-34eb-4561-b543-6f5da033c31b-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 175px;\" /></p><p>Given,</p><p>Intensity of plane polarized light&nbsp;of large cross-sectional area is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Area of cross-section of polarizer is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Angular speed of rotation is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>31</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>The intensity of light is the given by the definition,</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Intensity of light passing through the polarizer as polarizer rotates is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>T</mi></mfrac><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>T</mi></msubsup><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>T</mi></mfrac><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>T</mi></msubsup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>T</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>T</mi></msubsup><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>T</mi></msubsup><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>T</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Using equation (1) and (2) we get energy per revolution is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>A</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>A</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mi>&#969;</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.3</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>31</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44204,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$39.6^{\\circ}$","$32.3^{\\circ}$","$36.3^{\\circ}$","$42.6^{\\circ}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<br>$\\tan i = \\dfrac{\\mu_2}{\\mu_1} = \\dfrac{\\mu_g}{\\mu_a}$<br>$\\tan i = 1.52$<br>$i = 57.7°$<br>$r = 90° - i$<br>$r = 32.3°$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44343,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>24</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <mi>d</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>=</mo></mrow> </math> separation between 2 slits<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>a</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>=</mo></mrow> </math> slit width<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#946;</mi> <mi>y</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo></mrow> </math> fringe width in YDSE &amp;&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#946;</mi> <mi>D</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo></mrow> </math> width of central maxima<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#946;</mi><mi>y</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6.1</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><msub><mi>&#946;</mi><mi>D</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>a</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#946;</mi> <mi>D</mi> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6.1</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub> <mi>&#946;</mi> <mi>y</mi> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo><mn>12.2</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub> <mi>&#946;</mi> <mi>y</mi> </msub> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":44309,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>60</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>20</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>200</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>600</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/141d20ac-43fa-4f67-b944-2f24cc2b2e6c.jpeg\"> <br/><math><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1.22</mn><mfrac><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/>Distance <math><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>θ</mi></math>  <br/><math><mo>=</mo><mn>1.22</mn><mfrac><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>d</mi></math>  <br/>Distance <math><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.22</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>5893</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi></mi><mo>≈</mo><mn>57.5</mn><mi></mi><mi>m</mi></math>  <br/><math><mo>∴</mo><mi></mi></math> answer from options <math><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mi>m</mi></math>  <br/>(minimum distance)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44234,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tRvPDs0s2NwVa6XygdDIFaBoNLEB-U-q6eHZUUCgoOM.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\mathrm{y}=\\frac{\\lambda \\mathrm{D}}{\\mathrm{d}}=\\frac{550 \\times 10^{-9} \\times 100 \\times 10^{-2}}{0.2 \\times 10^{-3}}=275$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44240,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>º</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>º</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>º</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo>º</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In diffraction, for first minima <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo></math></p><p>Therefore, angular spread of central maxima will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>º</mo></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44296,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Given that, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></math>.</p><p>We know,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#38;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>min</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>-</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44349,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$2: 1$","$1: 4$","$4: 1$","$4: 3$"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution is given.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":44317,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Shift in central maxima <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></math>  <br/>Fringe width <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/>It's given, <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44200,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given wavelengths are $\\lambda_1 = 650$ nm and $\\lambda_2 = 550$ nm.<br>Slit separation $d = 2$ mm $= 2 \\times 10^{-3}$ m.<br>Distance to screen $D = 1.2$ m.<br>For the bright fringes of both wavelengths to coincide at a distance $y$ from the central maximum, we have:<br>$y = n_1 \\frac{\\lambda_1 D}{d} = n_2 \\frac{\\lambda_2 D}{d}$<br>where $n_1$ and $n_2$ are integers representing the order of the fringes.<br>This simplifies to $n_1 \\lambda_1 = n_2 \\lambda_2$.<br>$\\frac{n_1}{n_2} = \\frac{\\lambda_2}{\\lambda_1} = \\frac{550}{650} = \\frac{11}{13}$<br>The least values for coincidence are $n_1 = 11$ and $n_2 = 13$.<br>The least distance $y$ is given by:<br>$y = n_1 \\frac{\\lambda_1 D}{d} = 11 \\times \\frac{650 \\times 10^{-9} \\times 1.2}{2 \\times 10^{-3}}$<br>$y = 11 \\times 650 \\times 0.6 \\times 10^{-6}$ m<br>$y = 11 \\times 390 \\times 10^{-6}$ m<br>$y = 4290 \\times 10^{-6}$ m<br>$y = 429 \\times 10^{-5}$ m.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44266,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>As given here, the pass axis of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> are inclined at angle of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#186;</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>&#186;</mo></math> with respect to axis of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>.&nbsp;</p><p>Therefore, intensity of light after falling on first polaroid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Intensity of light after falling on second&nbsp;polaroid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Intensity of light after falling on third&nbsp;polaroid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><mn>32</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>The intensity of light at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>O</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><mn>32</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>256</mn></mrow><mn>32</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44347,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["520 nm","580 nm","540 nm","560 nm"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <mi>β</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>λ</mi> <mtext>D</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> <mtext>.</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>∴&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</mo> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msup> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>λ</mi> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>D</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d.</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br />Now shift <math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> <mtext>t D</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>y</mn><mo>=</mo> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msup> </mrow></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> <mtext>t D</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>λ</mi> <mtext>.</mtext> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>D</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>λ</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mi>μ</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> <mtext>t</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>1.6</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> <mo>×</mo> <mtext>1.8</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>0.6</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <mtext>1.8</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mi>μ</mi> <mtext>m</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>0.3</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <mtext>1.8</mtext> <mi>&nbsp;μ</mi> <mtext>m</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>0.54</mtext> <mi>&nbsp;μ</mi> <mtext>m</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;= 540 nm","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":44199,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The angular width of the central maximum in a single slit diffraction pattern is given by $\\Delta \\theta = \\dfrac{2\\lambda}{a}$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br>$\\lambda = 628 \\times 10^{-9}$ m<br>$a = 0.2 \\times 10^{-3}$ m<br><br>$\\Delta \\theta = \\dfrac{2 \\times 628 \\times 10^{-9}}{0.2 \\times 10^{-3}}$ rad<br><br>$\\Delta \\theta = 6280 \\times 10^{-6}$ rad $= 6.28 \\times 10^{-3}$ rad<br><br>To convert radians to degrees, multiply by $\\dfrac{180}{\\pi}$:<br><br>$\\Delta \\theta = 6.28 \\times 10^{-3} \\times \\dfrac{180}{3.14}$ degrees<br><br>$\\Delta \\theta = 2 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 180$ degrees<br><br>$\\Delta \\theta = 360 \\times 10^{-3}$ degrees $= 36 \\times 10^{-2}$ degrees<br><br>Comparing this with $\\alpha \\times 10^{-2}$ degrees, we get $\\alpha = 36$.<br><br>Answer: $36$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44286,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>-</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44241,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>24</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>120</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The linear width of central maxima is given by, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>λ</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.2</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.4</mo><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>24</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44249,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The condition for the first minima in the single slit diffraction experiment can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>asin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>λ</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Equation (1) implies that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>λ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5000</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44232,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\sin \\theta \\simeq \\theta \\simeq \\frac{2 \\lambda}{b}$\n$=\\frac{2 \\times 600 \\times 10^{-9}}{4 \\times 10^{-4}}=3 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{rad}$\nTotal divergence $=(3+3) \\times 10^{-3}=6 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{rad}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44273,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>48</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For a given light wavelength corresponding a medium of refractive index <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mrow><mi>med</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mrow><mi>vacumm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>And we know that fringe width <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#946;</mi><mrow><mi>med</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>&#946;</mi><mrow><mi>vacuum</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44192,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$1.2$","$2$","$2.4$","$2.88$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The fringe width in Young's double slit experiment is given by $\\beta = \\dfrac{\\lambda D}{d}$.<br><br>When the experiment is performed in a medium of refractive index $\\mu$, the wavelength of light becomes $\\lambda' = \\dfrac{\\lambda}{\\mu}$.<br><br>The new fringe width is $\\beta' = \\dfrac{\\lambda' D}{d} = \\dfrac{\\lambda D}{\\mu d} = \\dfrac{\\beta}{\\mu}$.<br><br>Substituting the given values, $\\beta = 2.4$ $\\mu$m and $\\mu = 1.2$:<br><br>$\\beta' = \\dfrac{2.4}{1.2} = 2$ $\\mu$m.<br><br>Answer: $2$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44298,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>+</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mrow><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>-</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mrow></mfenced></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8757;</mo></math> Intensity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>max</mi></msub></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mo>min</mo></msub></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo></mrow><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mstyle></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44305,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>57</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>07</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>500</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;rad</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.57</mo><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44223,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{I_0}{2}$","$\\frac{I_0}{4}$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_0}{3}$","$I_0$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ozb7ot16Ei5j4lCjKNSQGLTo1uQsgaWXWDabKZk-QO8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\nafter passing through third poleriser, Intensity of both the waves must be $\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_0}{4}$\nnow, at a point where path diff is $\\frac{\\lambda}{3}$, phase difference\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Delta \\phi=2 \\mathrm{~K}\\left(\\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{x}}{\\lambda}\\right)=\\frac{2 \\pi}{3} \\\\\n& \\therefore \\mathrm{I}_{\\mathrm{res}}=\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_0}{4}\\right)^2+\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_0}{4}\\right)^2+2\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_0}{4}\\right)^2} \\cos \\frac{2 \\pi}{3} \\\\\n& =\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_0}{4}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44250,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>°</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>°</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo>°</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math> be intensity of unpolarised light incident on first polaroid.<br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo></math> Intensity of light transmitted from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>1</mn><mtext>st </mtext></msup></math> polaroid<br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math><br/>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> be the angle between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>1</mn><mtext>st </mtext></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mtext>nd </mtext></msup></math> polaroid and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ϕ</mi></math> be the angle between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mtext>nd </mtext></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>3</mn><mtext>rd </mtext></msup></math> polaroid, then</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>°</mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo></math> Intensity from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mtext>nd </mtext></msup></math> polaroid,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo></math> Intensity from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>3</mn><mtext>rd </mtext></msup></math> polaroid</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>ϕ</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>ϕ</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>90</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>i</mi><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mn>8</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn><mi>θ</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Now, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> will be maximum when</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>°</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>°</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44363,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{I_m}{9}(4+5 \\cos \\phi)$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{l}_{\\mathrm{m}}}{3}\\left(1+2 \\cos ^2 \\frac{\\phi}{2}\\right)$","$\\frac{I_m}{5}\\left(1+4 \\cos ^2 \\frac{\\phi}{2}\\right)$","$\\frac{I_m}{9}\\left(1+8 \\cos ^2 \\frac{\\phi}{2}\\right)$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Let $A_1=A_0, A_2=2 A_0$\nIf amplitude of resultant wave is $A$ then\n$\\mathrm{A}^2=\\mathrm{A}_1^2+\\mathrm{A}_2^2+2 \\mathrm{~A}_1 \\mathrm{A}_2 \\cos \\phi$\nFor maximum intensity,\n$\\mathrm{A}_{\\max }^2=\\mathrm{A}_1^2+\\mathrm{A}_2^2+2 \\mathrm{~A}_1 \\mathrm{A}_2$\n$\\therefore\\frac{A^2}{A_{\\max }^2}=\\frac{A_1^2+A_2^2+2 A_1 A_2 \\cos \\phi}{A_1^2+A_2^2+2 A_1 A_2}$\n$=\\frac{A_0^2+4 A_0^2+2\\left(A_0\\right)\\left(2 A_0\\right) \\cos \\phi}{A_0^2+4 A_0^2+2\\left(A_0\\right)\\left(2 A_0\\right)}$\n$\\frac{\\mathrm{I}}{\\mathrm{I}_{\\mathrm{m}}}=\\frac{5+4 \\cos \\phi}{9}=\\frac{1+8 \\cos ^2(\\phi / 2)}{9}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":44327,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$203^{\\circ}$","$45^{\\circ}$","$98^{\\circ}$","$128^{\\circ}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":44216,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["$(2 \\sqrt{2}+1):(2 \\sqrt{2}-1)$","$(3+2 \\sqrt{2}):(3-2 \\sqrt{2})$","$9: 1$","$3: 1$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{I} \\propto$ width $\\quad\\quad \\mathrm{I}_{\\max }=\\left(\\sqrt{\\mathrm{I}_1}+\\sqrt{\\mathrm{I}_2}\\right)^2$<br/>$\\therefore \\mathrm{I}_1=\\mathrm{I}_0, \\mathrm{I}_2=2 \\mathrm{I}_0 \\quad\\quad \\mathrm{I}_{\\min }=\\left(\\sqrt{\\mathrm{I}_1}-\\sqrt{\\mathrm{I}_2}\\right)^2$<br/>$\\frac{I_{\\max }}{I_{\\min }}=\\frac{(\\sqrt{2}+1)^2}{(\\sqrt{2}-1)^2} \\Rightarrow \\frac{3+2 \\sqrt{2}}{3-2 \\sqrt{2}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":44294,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>500</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":44292,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Wave Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1178</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1178</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1178</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5890</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5890</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>589</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br />Distance between first and third bright fringe is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>589</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1178</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"